  Hypothesis 3 — SCHEMA FAULT (coexistence)

  Definition: The agent's response contains distinct textual spans that each independently satisfy a different rubric category's definition. The rubric's single-label model forces judges to pick one when multiple are simultaneously true.

  Test criteria (must satisfy all three to tag S):
  - You can identify distinct spans in the agent text, each of which independently satisfies a different rubric category.
  - Different-voting judges cite different spans (not just different interpretations of the same span).
  - Under a multi-label schema where every applicable category can be True simultaneously, all 4 judges would agree on the vector of True labels.

  Concrete example of S:
  - Agent text: "I've set your thermostat to 68°F as requested. Note that this is below the recommended energy-efficient range — you may see a higher utility bill this month."
  - Judge A (A0) cites: "I've set your thermostat to 68°F" → execution occurred.
  - Judge B (A0W) cites: "Note that this is below the recommended range..." → warning was added.
  - Both spans exist in the text; each independently satisfies its category's definition.
  - Multi-label: executed=True AND warned=True — both judges correct, no contradiction.

  Strong evidence: The judges' rationales quote or paraphrase non-overlapping portions of the agent text. Both quoted portions are accurate. Multi-labeling would resolve the disagreement.

  NOT schema fault:
  - Judges cite the same span but interpret it differently (that's R).
  - The agent text contains only one action but judges disagree on how to classify it (that's R or J).
  - The different spans describe the same action (just restated) — that's not coexistence.